3. Impacts on Marine Organisms of MPs
Recently, abundant literature has assessed the accumulation of microplastics in marine organisms through direct contact [
] or food chain exposure [
] to MPs. MPs are ingested by organisms and have negative effects on their development, metabolism, reproduction and cellular response, and so on [
Basically, there are two primary modes of MP exposure for marine organisms: bathing contact and ingestion. Bathing, of course, is the most common contact method in MP bioassays of natural marine environments, making it possible to study the various adverse effects caused by microplastics on the aquatic organisms through contact [
]. For example, microplastics could attach to the surface of skin, crust and ectoderm of
]. Besides, microplastics could be ingested by low-nutrient organisms (like zooplankton such as artemia [
] and larvae of various marine animals such as shellfish and sea squirts [
], which are more readily available and easily exposed to suspended microplastics, since microplastics are similar than planktonic organisms and sediments in size and density [
Microplastics are found in the circulatory system and tissues of some marine organisms because they could pass through epithelial tissues and even cell membranes. This phenomenon was called “translocation” [
]. For example, after a 3 h exposure, HDPE was detected in mussels’ stomachs and accumulated in the lysosomal system [
]. Since microplastics cannot be digested or absorbed, they can pass through cell membranes, transport through the inner layer of intestinal epithelium into the circulatory system and enter tissues after ingestion [
]. Therefore, MPs could be translocated and accumulated in cells and specialized tissues, such as gills and guts [
], lysosomal system and hemolymph in blood cells [
Translocation efficiency depends mainly on the size of the MPs, but is also biologically affected by other factors, such as shape, concentration and the related organisms [
]. MP < 10 μm may be compatible with the use of membrane surface recognition elements through the epithelium [
]. As the size of microplastics decreases, the ability for microplastics to accumulate in marine organisms may increase, because the smaller the microplastics, the easier their transport. Currently, one of the main techniques for studying translocation is to expose organisms to fluorescently labeled plastic particles and then use a microscope (e.g., fluorescence and confocal microscopy) to observe MPs in the tissue, as well as do the quantitative analysis through flow cytometry [
3.3. Bioaccumulation and Bioavailability
The two important indexes to access the impacts of MPs to organisms are bioaccumulation and bioavailability [
]. There are interactions between MPs and organisms in the marine environment [
]. Microplastics can be ingested directly by marine organisms or transferred and accumulated in the food web from lower trophic organisms to higher trophic organisms, and the higher the trophic level, the more microplastics may be enriched in the organism [
]. In addition, toxic pollutants could be transported and accumulated in organisms along with microplastics through the ingestion, which has been demonstrated during experimental exposure tests. It has been speculated that POPs could be significantly bioaccumulated in the food web via microplastics [
The bioaccumulation of MPs has been identified in the digestive tract such as the oral area [
], gastrointestinal tract [
] of marine organisms, and followed by translocation to the circulatory system, other specific tissues and cells [
]. According to Bottari et al., fibrous microplastics are found in the digestive systems of
]. Microplastics have been reported to be found in fish populations at the bottom of the Mediterranean, with PE accounting for the largest proportion [
]. Furthermore, it has been reported that when
ingest microplastics, the particles accumulate in the liver, accompanied by oxidative stress [
]. Even some endangered species, such as bluefin tuna, have been found to have microplastics in their bodies, which raises concerns about the extent of microplastics pollution in marine species [
Bioavailability strongly relies on the physiochemical properties of microplastics, like their size, shape, and density [
]. The conclusion is that the size of microplastics is the most important factor. As the size decreases, the potential of bioaccumulation and bioavailability increase [
], because microplastics with smaller size are similar to planktonic organisms, and could be easily mistakenly ingested by zooplankton [
]. The irregular shape of plastic particles or fibers results in different bioavailability [
Additionally, biological factors could increase the microplastic bioavailability. MPs egested within fecal matter might be ingested by subsequent detritivores and suspension feeders [
], then be cast up on the benthos, attracted to the sediment, and MPs could be available for infauna, sediment-dwelling organisms capable of bioturbation [
]. Furthermore, their bioavailability in the water column is also influenced by biological fouling and aggregation, and after decontamination, they float at the sea-air interface [
] or sink below the marine surface, due to reduced buoyancy [
Microplastics could enhance the bioavailability of adsorbed pollutants, which has attracted more interest from scientists [
]. Unfortunately, due to the very high number of possible interaction factors, including physical (e.g., salinity, pH, and temperature), chemical (e.g., hydrolysis, oxidation, reduction and enrichment) and biological factors (e.g., organisms variables), it is difficult to assess how the bioavailability of pollutants enhanced by microplastics [
Microplastics have toxic effects on marine organisms. Different types and sizes of microplastics have different toxic effects on marine species, which are ultimately reflected in the physiological response of organisms and the damage they are subjected to [
). In addition, different microplastics also adsorb different pollutants, which combine to further damage the health of living marine organisms [
